                <h4 class="noselect"  style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;">opinion articles</h4>
                <h6 class="noselect"  style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;text-align: center;"> <a href="outlines.html">outlines</a></h4>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('two')">Sixteenth of May 2021</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="two" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> Press and Proclamations: Who's More Threatened by Self-Expression?</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://www.rappler.com/moveph/with-anti-terror-law-red-tagged-campus-press-struggle-report-coronavirus-pandemic">Red-tagging: a threat to press freedom and democracy</a></em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>Mediums of communication, may it be the air, a text message, or a Tweet flung across the Internet for the world to see, are readily available and easily obtainable by average Filipinos, but that doesn't mean that they're ready to go all out and shout, "I hate my neighbor's noisy dog; I wish he would just die," right? <br>
                <br> The 1987 Constitution, Article III, Section 4 announces that "no law shall be passed abridging the freedom of speech, of expression, or the press..." Since the law recognizes everyone, whether you, your friends, the creepy guy at the terminal, or the terrorists living here, it's pretty evident that it implies how we can deliver ourselves effortlessly since nothing cannot stop us from prohibiting it.<br>
                <br> Of course, a criticized example of this situation is the sinister Anti-Terrorism Law of 2020. Neri Colmenares, Human Rights Lawyer, speaks on how this proclamation threatens the freedom of expression since it indicates how it could punish people who instigate others in executing terrorism "by means of speeches, proclamations, writings, emblems, banners or other representations tending to the same end." Contradictingly, a study led by Martin Obschonka, an associate professor at the Queensland University of Technology, discovered how people's characteristics could be formulated through digital self-expression, specifically, Tweets, where vulnerabilities can be scientifically observed. Even actions like stalking our crush on Facebook to discover that he likes challenges and hating dictators make us guilty of judging their lives based on software.<br>
                <br> Behind a screen, there's no telling if a person is capable of anything. The Cybercrime Prevention Act of 2012 does not also include how investigating social media activities are seen as violations of human rights. It presents a conclusion that the Federal Bureau of Investigation can legally snoop in and out of our accounts and subjecting public posts to the possibility that it can be a threat to national security. Since there's no need to indicate opinions that may put your reputation at risk, what is there to fear? Having proclamations that prohibit the freedom of expression, particularly the Anti-Terrorism Law of 2020, save us from the dangers of too much freedom granted to us. If we can stop verbally abusing others for their sake, why don't we establish it digitally? This controversial law is proven to make the country a better place. Poland, for example, flexes the same condition as the Philippines. As stated by the International Center for Counter-Terrorism, its National Threat Level is at 0% since the establishment of its Anti-Terrorism Law compared to the Philippines' Global Terrorism Index, which also declined after President Duterte signed the said bill.
                <br>
                <br> These limits imposed on the freedom of expression are also applied to campus journalists who write their way to push their liberty. What is there to fight against if the Anti-Terrorism Law of 2020 protects ourselves from the temptations of too much freedom? Comparing it to the Bayanihan to Heal as One Act, strict quarantines can be considered violations of our civil liberties; why people follow it is evident since it
                presents a physical limitation. <br>
                <br> Complementarily, a statement by Charles Friend in The Harvard Gazette brandishes how "the
                liberties of getting where you want to go are less concerning than the potential for disinformation and
                rumor-mongering." After all, even the United States of America includes laws that recognize the
                limitations of freedom of speech if it inflicts damage to the other party involved. <br>
                <br> The Ericsson Mobility Report reveals that in 2021, smartphone users in the Philippines will hit 90
                million; that's the same amount of people who have a right to express their disagreement, dangerous
                views, possible threats, and troublesome plans about the government. We might be wondering, "Does
                everything I say defines who I am today?" According to the Anti-Terror Law of 2020, it's a "Yes!" <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/16/2022</h6>
                <p style="font-size: 12px;font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;"><em>The remnants of National Campus Press Olympiad 2021- did I tell you that my classmate basically dragged me, having no speck of experience in editorial writing, in participating? Yes, I did not win haha but who cares? *drowns in mispellings and wrong grammar* I feel like my point is dragged so much, the article seems like an overshaken mango shake... does that make sense? like my article, it's a definite no. Agh, I wish I could express myself better. I mean, I'm doing this for the sake of organizing what's in my mind first before thinking about others. What's the use of writing for the audience if I don't even know what my thoughts are.</em></p><small style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-size: 12px;"><br></small>
