                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('three')">Seventh of June 2021</a></h6>
                <div class="mid" id="three" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;">Lies After Lies: History Forgotten Leaves Public Dumbfounded</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> Based on a webinar conducted by the High School Philippine History Movement [1/3] </em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>Sudden changes in the Department of Education’s curriculum pursued the removal of Philippine History, leaving the masses with an impaired ability to determine the differences between the South China Sea and the West Philippine Sea. This controversial territorial dispute gained the popularity it instilled in social networking sites such as Facebook and Twitter. Since fake news circulated the Internet, and these alterations can twist the public, the issues regarding to ditching the historical background of the Philippines as a high school subject remained up for debate. Does the lack of knowledge about the Philippine History, especially when it comes to territories, affect the public’s understanding of the differences between the rightful name of the sea? Absolutely, yes!<br>
                <br> Fake news has circulated the Internet; most prominent alterations observed in popular social media sites, such as Facebook and Twitter. With a lack of background knowledge, most Filipinos may interchangeably use South China Sea or the West Philippine Sea as a name pertaining to a single body of water. Even the Chief Presidential Legal Counsel Salvador Panelo was recently confused about the disparities between China’s self-proclaimed territory and the Philippines’ zone. After the ABS-CBN News Channel reported this complication on YouTube, hundreds of comments ranted on how lies were being fed by the same government they voted on. Our freedom of information, even though it is still accessible, became shrouded by the order the Department of Education imposed. How important is Philippine History among elementary pupils when high school students like us can actually have the ability to change the world?<br>
                <br>We must fear how the fast-paced millennium will soon turn truth to rumors. The critical thinking we can pursue through the implementation of Philippine History in the high school curriculum will change every perspective for the better. In accordance with what High School Philippine History Movement President Jamaico D. Ignacio stated, social media encourages historical distortions and historical revisionism. Our history became vulnerable to change! What would this incident lead to? False information, manipulated facts, and changed perceptions will change the Philippines in unpredictable ways.<br>
                <br>The fiasco between the rightful name of the sea between the Philippines’ and China’s may start to worsen, especially when the Filipinos themselves remained confused on how to identify their territories versus the Chinese. As stated by the University of the Philippines Institute for Maritime Affairs and Law of the Sea professor Jay Batongbacal in an ABS-CBN report, an international tribunal finalized the Philippines’ rule of the West Philippine Sea, as opposed to the fake news circulating that our nation has no right over the said territory. If this fabrication from the Internet continued to manipulate the minds of the Filipinos, we might have gone against a government who may be doing the best they can for our sake.
                <br>
                <br>Lies, lies, lies. Everything may be a lie, but if published Philippine History lecture books state otherwise, we will have a chance to prey on what is right. <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/16/2022</h6>
