                </div>


                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('one')">Seventh of June 2021</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="one" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> The Past Creates Your Identity: Prioritize It!</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em>Based on a webinar conducted by the High School Philippine History Movement [2/3]</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>A democratic government like the Philippines stands high and mighty because of the people that voted in favor of its excellence and integrity, but if individuality became compromised caused by one’s lack of insight of the past, Generations X and Alpha may transform for the worst.<br>
                <br>The significance of individuality came from the High School Philippine History Movement’s stance to bring back Philippine History as a high school subject that strengthens critical thinking, in contradiction to the memorization-based technique. If this trait is overlooked, the Department of Labor and Employment will encounter thousands of college graduates who lack the essential competencies. The inadequacy of lessons on the Philippine History risks this possibility, but this will not be the end of the crisis.<br>
                <br> In critical thinking, objectivity in analysis of an argument prevails. We can also gain this skill from other subjects, such as Mathematics, English, and Science, but History instigates the growth of loyalty to one’s nation. A study published also determined how self-identity and nationalism bonds, so did the Department of Health need to remove the Philippines’ past as a high school subject when it serves as the beacon that uncovers who we are? No way!<br>
                <br>The drop of critical thinkers prevails in our generation, which similarly alters the next millennium. Logical reasoning and evaluation continue to fail our expectations to the children left to reinvigorate the world. Social issues, specially poverty and homelessness, can be addressed properly if students gain continuous lessons that encourage critical thinking, which boost their self-identity. Have you encountered a fellow Filipino delighted with his individuality and embracing his nationalism? What would our majestic nation be like if Filipinos know more about their past and become critical thinkers that understand issues through a well-meaning self-identity?
                <br>
                <br> The Filipinos’ individuality connects with the Philippine democracy, and critical thinking manipulates the state of knowing oneself. The crisis highlighting the lack of this skill influences one’s self-identity that disrupts significant aspects in one’s life. Studying Philippine History as a high school student will dramatically improve their well-being, as opposed to memorization proven to heighten their stress levels. An hour of history, with open-ended questions about forgotten controversies, is better than mathematical jargons that everyone needs to learn by heart even though more of them long to be a journalist.<br>
                <br>As the saying goes, the past predicts the present, which affects the future. Will you choose to forget the Philippines’ previous experiences or encourage its reinstatement for every Filipino who longs to be critical thinkers that would fight for what is true? <br>
                <br>Prioritize the past! Let it refine you! <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/16/2022</h6>
