                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('four')">Eighth of January 2022</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="four" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> The Questionable New Names of Quarantine</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> For a four-page newsletter in Media and Information Literacy</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>As replacement for the accustomed community quarantines, the alert level system has been the catalyst for Filipinos to have confusing thoughts and misleading beliefs on which guidelines are implemented.<br>
                <br>
Since before the COVID-19 pandemic happened, various cases involving incomprehensible rules were already threatening our basic human rights. There have been articles in the 1987 Philippine Constitution that speak of punishment through poor phrasing, which, in turn, leaves the interpretation to individuals who can manipulate these seemingly capable words to their favor. For instance, people who committed so-called “unjust vexations” could actually be punished with either a hefty fine or imprisonment wherein the definition for the actual crime is ambiguous; to put it simply, this offense could range from minor annoyances up to a disturbing karaoke party late at night. How these words are constructed can inflict either harm or goodwill to the individuals subjected to it. In this case, there is no need for the Inter-Agency Task Force to modify the names and make the quarantine restrictions more complicated than it actually is.<br>
<br>
As campaigned by President Rodrigo Duterte, change is coming. However, how does these changes benefit us if all we experience are constant, unrelenting modifications that trigger our fear of the future? The COVID-19 pandemic came off as a shock that transformed the world we are used to into something that is far stranger than we have ever encountered. More importantly, the newly developed alert level system does not actually help us adjust at all; in fact, its implementation suggests that the government already expects a degree of herd immunity developing among us, even though they have barely started the vaccination process. Overestimating our adaptability to environmental changes puts everyone in a tight spot. If worse comes to worst, what good will these brief moments of exemptions be?<br>
<br>
All of us long for the day we could all rip the masks off our faces and breathe the air like how we were before the pandemic happened. This hope is not meant to be tainted with hasty implementations of an alert level system that confuses and distorts the way we adjust in accordance to our surroundings. For this reason, the Inter-Agency Task Force does not have to complicate matters and make the guidelines more incomprehensible than ever. Easing quarantine restrictions comes with higher risks in contracting the disease. As we try to adapt and survive against the unpredictable, we should never forget that the virus is also trying to live with us as its enemies. With the rise of the present-day alert level system, the changes we are used to are slowly becoming lax. When our invisible adversary hits us where it hurts the most, who knows what will happen if we remain adamant on the questionable new names of quarantine.<br>

                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/17/2022</h6>
