            </div>



                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('five')">Twelfth of February 2022</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="five" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> President’s Decree: No!</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> ICC Prosecution of Duterte (a practice article for Division Schools Press Conference 2022)</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>With seats of power on the verge of replacement and legal immunity drawing to a close, Rodrigo Duterte must take responsibility for all the innocent lives damaged by his infamous war on drugs, and that is, by adhering to the International Criminal Court’s investigation on his bloody six-year term as President of the Philippines. <br>
                <br>A campaign built upon various threats, disrespectful remarks, and intimidating statements against criminals enabled Rodrigo Duterte to win the 2016 Presidential elections. He captured the hearts of the poor who were afflicted with countless decisions involving illegal measures to escape the difficulties of poverty. Unexpectedly, Duterte responded to these malice through a shoot-to-kill order for illegal drug suspects. With additional power over his commandeered police force, the line between prosecution and execution blurred against the poor. Duterte’s words disregarded the presumption of their innocence. <br>
                <br>Filed by the International Criminal Court (ICC), cases against Duterte caught up with him. When cooperation is expected, Duterte fired back statements that ICC representatives will be denied entry to the country amid an authority to investigate since they no longer have any jurisdiction when the Philippines left the said organization in March 2019. To the public, he gave out remarks on how he could run for vice president over and over again to maintain a status of absolute immunity over these cases. With words that are as fickle as the wind, Duterte used his current position to say no against the tribunal and it is not illegal to do so. <br>
                <br>In contrast to the Philippine President’s claim, the International Criminal Court (ICC) did not abuse their authority in the implementation of their full-blown investigation on his war on drugs. They replied that this case will involve facts that happened before the country withdrew from the organization, starting from November 2011. Accordingly, Duterte’s insistence on running for vice president to gain legal immunity was refuted as he recently proclaimed his resignation to politics. If he is as guilty as the ICC says, his prosecution will finally silence the cries of the victims of his reign, regaining human rights infringed by his word. <br>
                <br>With or without power, President Rodrigo Duterte must remain cooperative in proving that he is not guilty in the midst of his term’s extrajudicial killings. The second he is replaced as the highest authority in the country, no legal implications and hasty words will make him escape the fate of being the catalyst of countless Filipinos killed from his method on the Philippines’ war on drugs. Duterte should focus on fighting the cases against him head-on without heading to the hills. In times where his words become power, President Duterte must make sure that the responsibility coming with it is in accordance with his actions, even as a private citizen in his beloved country. <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/17/2022</h6>
