                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('six')">Thirteenth of February 2022</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="six" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> WITNESSassin</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> Immunity of Arturo Lascañas (a practice article for Division Schools Press Conference 2022)</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>With his past as Rodrigo Duterte’s Davao Death Squad (DDS) hitman and accessory to its crimes, Arturo Lascañas is both a witness and a criminal; that being said, the International Criminal Court’s decision to grant him limited immunity for his self-inflicting confessions is justice in its own way.<br>
                <br>Revealing the truth after years of cover-ups and evasion is hard enough but securing a confession can make or break a case, even if it comes from the mouth of the bad guy himself. As an individual, Arturo Lascañas can be suspected with untold criminal cases and involvement with the Davao Death Squad. He declared that this group followed kill orders from Rodrigo Duterte, former Mayor of Davao City and current President of the Philippines. In spite of how this confession affects the case, Lascañas’ accusations does not mean that he is exempted from the crimes he committed himself. The limited immunity given to him by the International Criminal Court (ICC) prevents him from self-incriminating himself but, as International Center for Transitional Justice (ICTJ) senior expert Ruben Carranza said, Arturo Lascañas’ immunity is only for the prosecution for the ICC’s investigation of Duterte’s drug war and the alleged DDS.<br>
                <br>Without the limited immunity deal between ICC’s Office of the Prosecutor (OTP) and him, Lascañas’ words could be lost forever, especially when his life is as dangerous as the circumstances he confessed to. The possibility of him being prosecuted by his country housing the squad he betrayed heightens. With Senate investigations terminated by his want to testify, the only option Arturo Lascañas has is to protect himself through the international court. According to ICTJ lawyer Carranza, Lascañas’ words are the key in determining the decision on who will be charged for these crimes and finally solving the cases involving Duterte and his Davao Death Squad. All Filipinos need to know the truth behind this intricate web of accusations so the country should also cut this whistleblower some slack and proceed to protect him until justice reigns all. <br>
                <br>As a former assassin and a vital witness, Arturo Lascañas’ limited immunity from his confession is the best way to bring justice to Filipino lives affected by Duterte's drug war and the Davao Death Squad’s presence. The Philippines must also help this man shed light to the words he spoke of and cooperate with the International Criminal Court. Everyone deserves to know what really happened in these past few years, and with the witness-assin Arturo Lascañas’ protection, the truth may prevail after all. <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/17/2022</h6>
                <p style="font-size: 12px;font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;"><em> I'm cringing at myself! What kind of title is that? </em></p><small style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-size: 12px;"><br></small>
            </div>


                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('seven')">Thirteenth of February 2022</a></h6>
            <div class="mid" id="seven" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> Questiona-BILL</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> Approval of House Bill No. 7814 (a practice article for Division Schools Press Conference 2022)</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>When mere speculations can convict countless Filipinos accused of illegal drug crimes, the approval of House Bill No. 7814 drives fear into the hearts of the innocent, replacing their trust with dread as they fear assumptions that can sentence them as guilty— even if they are innocent.<br>
                <br>As a fiercer way to implement the Republic Act No. 9165, also known as the Comprehensive Dangerous Drugs Act of 2002, HB 7814 gives more power to law enforcement agents. A provision states how a person is first presumed to be guilty with drug-related crimes, may it be abetting an escape or possessing importation receipts, before he could prove it otherwise. When this bill becomes law, the usual ‘innocent until proven guilty’ will be reversed when it comes to accusations involving illegal drugs. As understood by Jesus Suntay, House committee on human rights chair, his vote in favor of HB 7814  will be convicting the accused through speculations, which is an act he does not approve of. Proper investigations on drug-related suspects could be overlooked and hasty assumptions might prevail. Those who are framed for their involvement could have their lives stuck on imprisonment when they are actually blameless.<br>
                <br>	In another perspective, the terror House Bill No. 7814 brings is effective against sought-after drug personalities who remained unscathed because of the tame nature of RA 9165. According to Robert Ace Barbers, House committee on dangerous drugs chair, law enforcers armed with legal presumptions will have the chance to put the evasive accused over the same pedestal as the suspected drug criminals. Regardless, everyone will be overpowered by this bill when the time comes. When the line between ifs and innocence becomes blurry because of HB 7814, must the country wait for spilled blood before realizing that turning this bill into law is as bad as it gets?<br>
                <br>	The harsh nature of a law might be present but at the end of the day, it is still the law. Unfortunately, time is running out before House Bill No. 7814 amends RA 9165, making those involved with drugs guilty before they are innocent. When hasty conclusions are at bay, Philippine prisons could be filled with scapegoats and framed individuals. With this questionable bill, who knows how many civilian lives could be jeopardized in the hands of law. <br>
                </p>
                <br>
                <h6 style="font-family: Overpass, sans-serif;font-weight: bold;font-size: 12px;">comment | 02/17/2022</h6>
