                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('eight')">Fourteenth of February 2022</a></h6>
                <div class="mid" id="eight" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> After DISTRUST-ers</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> Government's inaction on disasters (a practice article for Division Schools Press Conference 2022)</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>Smiling faces turn into frowns as typhoon-affected Filipinos claim: how long should they be resilient when disasters come? Sure enough, the famed bayanihan can help them live for so but after all this time, the government should be embarrassed about their inaction towards their suffering subjects. Nobody is at fault for the harsh typhoons that wrecked homes and livelihoods but the aftermath must be handled by those with power. These disasters fuel distrust among the public to their leader more than the independence they are expected of.<br>
                <br>As Philippine president Rodrigo Duterte lamented that the budget is “immensely depleted,” he still promised a Php 10 billion allocation. While Filipinos drown and despair, he spoke of an amount that may or may not reach the affected in time. The implications of his words are endless; is he saying that bayanihan must help first before the government’s response? Duterte is basically giving the lives of his people into their own hands. He could have thought of something different to make sure that Filipinos could have had their lives easier. His inaction is distressing; it should be easier for him to express his compassion as having the highest position of power. <br>
                <br>The self-reliance of Filipinos may be a good thing but after everything that has happened, what if this empathy wanes? It may be the citizens’ responsibility to look after each other but with the government who possesses the most resources and the highest authority, it must make enough laws to fuel hope for tomorrow even after disasters. In all of the years the Philippines stood against its fight against the weather, the President must focus on regaining the public’s trust through relief operations and sustainable solutions. If he is willing to take action, countless organizations are willing to pair up with him. Bayanihan involves everyone, and with more power, the greater amount of help is given to the affected.<br>
                <br>When disasters end, distrust soon arrives. How this country’s politicians become indifferent to its citizens does not show an inkling on what a public-serving government should be. With everybody familiar with the progressing disasters that arrive, the President and other governmental organizations should have plans regarding the safety of the society. When lives are being lost and expectance becomes acceptance, will power even matter for the people?<br>
                </p>
                <br>
