                <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('nine')">Fourteenth of February 2022</a></h6>
                <div class="mid" id="nine" style="display: none;">
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> Un-PRESIDENT-ed</p>
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> Vague Marcos agenda (a practice article for Division Schools Press Conference 2022)</em></p>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;
                <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
                <br>Like that obstinate friend dragging us to that God-forsaken roller-coaster ride, Ferdinand “Bong Bong” Marcos, Jr. is leading the country through plastic promises of unity and reformation; meanwhile, the road ahead of us remains unmapped.<br>
                <br>We are all familiar with how political campaigning works: catchy jingles, candidate-defining colors, and soundbites presenting their agenda for the next few years. Accordingly, every presidential candidate has their own method of winning our hearts but their actions all answer one question: If elected as the President of the Philippines, what can you do for the Filipinos? Bong Bong Marcos answers, guess what? Unity! As stated in an article from Rappler, his Uniteam (with running mate Sara Duterte) said cooperation is the key for this “new society” he’s planning to lead us into. He’s campaigning for change when in reality, this Junior is using the dead dictator’s legacy to claim more votes! All the media knows about him is how he stubbornly revives the compromised image of Ferdinand Marcos, Sr.. If he sits in the highest position of the country, will he conjure the ghost of his father to seek advice? Marcos, Jr. is not his father; he neither has his achievements nor his eloquence. Why should the public vote for a child borrowing the face of his father?
                <br>
                <br>Yes, he is not Marcos, Sr. but at the same time, he is. Bong Bong can just make the Philippines better, like the first half of his father’s reign, and prevent the oppressive Martial Law from happening again. Easy, right? No! In comparison to his Uniteam, other presidential candidates have more detailed plans expressed through televised debates and clear-as-day campaigns. His vague agenda leads the country into a world of unknown and with our worsening state, how does he plan to drag us away from hell with only “unity” in mind?<br>
                <br>Rome wasn’t built in a day, and surely, their plans to build it weren’t just a big unity word scribbled across a page. Ferdinand Marcos, Jr. should try elaborating what his campaign is all about. Is it a farce to fool Filipinos that we’re looking at his impressive but oppressive father? Is the entirety of his plan focused on winning the hearts of everyone while the country’s economy falls? Will his win give us a breath of fresh air and think, this son is finally paying for his father’s sins?<br>
                <br>In the 2022 Presidential elections, Bong Bong Marcos may carry the image of his father but no matter how related they are, he will not be as good as him. Junior’s credentials, tact, and presence is a shadow to what Marcos supporters expect him to be. This roller-coaster ride is not what the Philippines currently needs. Inside a dark cave with BBM claiming light, the public must not trust him because we know he cannot make one.<br>
                </p>
                <br>
