              <h6 style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;font-weight: bold;text-align: center;"><a onclick="javascript:ShowHide('eleven')">Third of March 2022</a></h6>
              <div class="mid" id="eleven" style="display: none;">
              <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"> ABCs of New Normal</p>
              <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: center;"><em> editorial writing random article generator: source nine </a> . </em></p>
              &nbsp;&nbsp;
              <p style="font-family: 'Overpass Mono', monospace;text-align: left;"
              <br>Normalcy defined our world; well, not until the COVID-19 happened. Three years after, our nation is still stuck within its comfort zone, believing that the reopening of our economy meant coronavirus resurgence. However, everyone already has the scar symbolizing these changes that we are now used to. With both knowledge and bravery, we are more than prepared to face the new normal.
  <br> <br>
	Starting with Metro Manila, the government should start downgrading the alert levels assigned to each province when they fulfill certain conditions. Like what a Rappler article concluded, the average daily attack rate and the reproduction number of the virus of the region already fulfilled the World Health Organization’s standards: a country with less than 5% positivity rate can start reopening its economy. As survivors of the pandemic, we are used to the virus preventive measures and the corresponding inoculation process. With our knowledge as shield and the COVID-19 vaccine as our spear, what are we afraid of?<br> <br>
	Still, the lingering anxieties of our mind are shouting: the COVID-19 pandemic has not turned into an endemic; therefore, it is better to retreat than advance against our invisible enemy. What is there to fear when everybody knows how to keep themselves safe from the virus? For the past three years, we have been bombarded with information on what to do and how to survive against the disease. With this knowledge, we are already facing our fear of dying! How we have studied the coronavirus and vaccinated ourself against it are indications that we are embracing how this change could affect our future. Why must we stop at that?<br> <br>
When adversity comes, bravery must prevail before cowardice. With our modern technologies and intelligent data analysts, the Philippines is more than prepared to welcome the new society defined by the COVID-19 pandemic. Living in the new normal is not an easy task, per se, since both the rewards and the risks are too high. Accordingly, our government already anticipated and calculated what choices must be chosen. Don’t forget, the ABCs of new normal are as easy as it gets! <br>
              </p>
